West Nile fever, Greece
-----------------------
Information received on (and dated) 29 Sep 2010 from Mr Spiros
Doudounakis, Head, Department of Infectious Diseases, Directorate
General of Veterinary Services, Animal Health Directorate, Department
of Infectious Diseases, Ministry of Rural Development and Food,
Athens, Greece

Summary
Report type: follow-up report no. 1
Start date: 16 Aug 2010
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 23 Aug 2010
Report date: 29 Sep 2010
Date submitted to OIE: 29 Sep 2010
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: West Nile virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to the whole country
Related reports: immediate notification (27 Aug 2010); follow-up
report no. 1 (29 Sep 2010)

New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 7
Total animals affected
Species: Equidae
Susceptible: 37
Cases: 7
Deaths: 1
Destroyed: 1
Slaughtered: 0

Outbreak statistics
Species: Equidae
Apparent morbidity rate: 18.92 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 2.70 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 14.29 percent
Proportion susceptible animals lost*: 5.41 percent
* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction,
and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Control measures
Measures applied: screening; no vaccination; treatment of affected
animals (supportive treatment [dexamethasone, furosemide, neurobion,
NSAID/nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs])
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Center of Athens Veterinary Institutes,
Institute of Infectious and Parasitic Diseases, Virology Department
(national laboratory)
Species: Equidae
Test: competitive ELISA (c-ELISA)
Test date: 27 Sep 2010
Result: positive

Species: Equidae
Test: IgM-capture ELISA
Test date: 27 Sep 2010
Result: positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The update report from Spain covers 14 farms that are spread over a
wide area in Andalusia, the most southern part of Spain that borders
the Straits of Gibraltar. Likewise, in Macedonia, Greece, the 7 farms
are spread over a wide geographic area. Vaccination is an effective
control measure but it may be that the epidemic won't end until there
is a hard frost, which will reduce the transmission of the West Nile
virus to horses by killing off the mosquito populations.

The follow up no. 1 report from Spain has quite an interesting anomaly
which I have rarely seen while watching OIE WAHID reports for over a
decade -- there are no diagnostic test reports to confirm the
diagnosis of West Nile virus in horses from the 14 farms. In the
original report from Spain both IgM capture ELISA and competitive
ELISA were used to identify positive horses. I suspect the same tests
were used to confirm the horses in follow up report no. 1.

The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the maps appended to the
respective OIE-WAHID reports
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Spain is available at
<http://healthmap.org/r/0bjj>
and of Greece at
<http://healthmap.org/r/026S>. - Mod. PC]
